const faqs = [{"question": "What is the best peptide for visceral fat?", "answer": "Tesamorelin is the peptide with the strongest evidence for visceral fat specifically — it is FDA-approved to reduce visceral adipose tissue and was studied directly for that purpose. Ipamorelin and CJC-1295 also mobilize visceral fat as GH secretagogues but are not FDA-approved for it. Because visceral fat sits deep around the organs and carries the most metabolic risk, the best choice depends on your labs and overall metabolic picture, which a physician evaluates before prescribing."}, {"question": "How do peptides target visceral fat?", "answer": "GH secretagogue peptides raise your own growth hormone, and visceral (deep abdominal) fat is especially responsive because it carries a higher density of growth hormone receptors than subcutaneous fat. That means GH-mediated lipolysis mobilizes visceral fat preferentially, which is why peptides like Tesamorelin can reduce belly and organ fat even when overall weight changes modestly. This is measured objectively with imaging such as a DEXA scan rather than the bathroom scale."}, {"question": "Can peptides reduce visceral fat without major weight loss?", "answer": "Yes — this is a key distinction. Peptides like Tesamorelin are studied for reducing visceral fat and improving body composition rather than driving large drops in total body weight. Patients often see a flatter midsection and improved metabolic markers with only modest scale changes, because the fat being mobilized is metabolically active visceral tissue. For dramatic total-weight reduction, GLP-1 medications are usually more appropriate."}, {"question": "Can peptides specifically target belly fat?", "answer": "Growth hormone secretagogues promote lipolysis (fat breakdown) throughout the body, but research shows that visceral (belly) fat is particularly responsive to growth hormone's lipolytic effects. Visceral fat has a higher density of growth hormone receptors, making it more susceptible to GH-mediated fat mobilization."}, {"question": "How long before I see results with GH peptides?", "answer": "Most patients notice improvements in body composition within 4–8 weeks, with optimal results typically seen at 3–6 months. Early changes include improved sleep quality and recovery, with visible body composition changes following. Results depend on adherence to nutrition and exercise recommendations."}, {"question": "Are GH secretagogues the same as HGH injections?", "answer": "No. GH secretagogues stimulate your body's own production of growth hormone through the pituitary gland, maintaining natural pulsatile release patterns. Exogenous HGH injections bypass this system entirely, carrying a higher risk of side effects and pituitary suppression."}, {"question": "Do I need to exercise while using peptides for fat loss?", "answer": "While peptides can improve body composition independently, results are significantly better when combined with regular resistance training and cardiovascular exercise. Exercise also stimulates natural GH release, creating a synergistic effect with peptide therapy."}, {"question": "Will peptides help with loose skin after fat loss?", "answer": "Growth hormone plays a role in collagen synthesis and skin elasticity. Some patients report improved skin quality alongside fat loss, though this is not a primary indication. For collagen-specific support, explore our guide on collagen peptides."}, {"question": "Is tesamorelin FDA-approved?", "answer": "Yes. Tesamorelin (brand name Egrifta) received FDA approval in 2010 for the reduction of excess abdominal fat in HIV-infected patients with lipodystrophy. It is used off-label for body composition optimization under physician supervision."}];

